The '''{{lang|ht|Akademi Kreyòl Ayisyen}}''' ({{IPA-ht|akademi kɣejɔl ajisjɛ̃}}), known in English as the '''Haitian Creole Academy''', is the [[List of language regulators|language regulator]] of [[Haitian&nbsp;Creole]].<ref name="Dizikes2015">{{cite web |url=https://news.mit.edu/2015/3-questions-michel-degraff-haiti-teaching-kreyol-0720 |title=3 Questions: Michel DeGraff on Haiti's new policy for teaching in Kreyòl |work=MIT News |date=20 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906185229/http://news.mit.edu/2015/3-questions-michel-degraff-haiti-teaching-kreyol-0720 |archive-date=6 September 2015 |dead-url=no |last=Dizikes |first=Peter |publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts}}</ref> It is composed of up to 55{{nbsp}}scholars under the leadership of [[Pauris&nbsp;Jean‑Baptiste]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lenational.ht/akademi-kreyol-ayisyen-aka-ant-reyalizasyon-ak-pespektiv/ |title=Akademi Kreyòl Ayisyen (AKA): Ant reyalizasyon ak pèspektiv |work=Le National |date=6 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124001952/http://lenational.ht/akademi-kreyol-ayisyen-aka-ant-reyalizasyon-ak-pespektiv/ |archive-date=24 January 2016 |dead-url=no |language=ht |location=Port‑au‑Prince}}</ref>

==History==
The Haitian Creole language did not have any regulation until the 1940s, when former Haitian president, [[Élie Lescot]] made attempts at standardizing the language. It had an official orthography by the late 1970s, and it was elevated to being the official language in the [[Haitian Constitution|1987 Haitian Constitution]]. The language still lacked an academy to regulate its evolution until about 25 years later.

==Background==
In December 2014, the Haitian president and legislation approved of the establishment of the Haitian Creole Academy. 33 scholars came together and formed the organization to form a uniformed syntax, to ensure the Haitian government is able to better communicate with its people, lead the way for more publications of books and various other forms of media, and to end the stigma behind speaking the language. The AKA recently{{when|date=July 2018}} published a new alphabet and {{clarify span|set of rules.|date=July 2018}}

