The '''Party Human Environment Animal Protection''' ({{lang-de|Partei Mensch Umwelt Tierschutz}}, short form: '''Animal Protection Party''', {{lang-de|Tierschutzpartei}}) is a [[political party]] in [[Germany]], founded in 1993. In 2014 one candidate was elected to the [[European Parliament]]. As of December 2014 the party has no members in the state parliaments, the European Parliament or the [[Bundestag]].

== Overview ==
The party aspires to turn away from the [[Anthropocentrism|anthropocentric]] view of life. Its main goal is the introduction of more [[animal rights]] into the [[Basic Law of the Federal Republic of Germany|German constitution]]. Those include the right to live and the protection from physical and psychological damages. The Tierschutzpartei also demands prohibition of [[animal testing]], [[bullfighting]], [[hunting]], the production of [[fur]]s, [[circus]] [[Animal training|animal]]s and agricultural [[animal husbandry]], as well as the adaptation of the people to [[veganism]]. The party supports a ban on [[genetic engineering]] and wants a reduction of car [[traffic]] and an immediate exit from [[Nuclear power|nuclear energy]]. Economically it supports more social justice, a stamp duty and a free basic income.

In the [[European Parliament election, 2014 (Germany)|2014 European parliament elections]], the Animal Protection Party received 1.25% of the national vote (366,303 votes in total) and returned one [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]], [[Stefan Eck]], who sits with the [[EUL-NGL]].<ref>[http://www.bundeswahlleiter.de/de/europawahlen/EU_BUND_14/ergebnisse/bundesergebnisse/ Bundesergebnis] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705072802/http://www.bundeswahlleiter.de/de/europawahlen/EU_BUND_14/ergebnisse/bundesergebnisse/ |date=2015-07-05 }}</ref> In December 2014 Eck left the party and became an independent MEP in the EUL-NGL-group.

